Re: Proposed N.C. Budget Cuts in DHR: Whitaker School and Wright School
Dear Governor Perdue:
I am writing this letter to express disappointment and opposition to the proposed budget cuts that would result in the closing of both the Whitaker School and the Wright School.  These two programs currently serve some of the most emotionally disturbed, at-risk students in the state.  It would be an extremely shortsighted decision for both humanitarian and fiscal reasons for these services to be cut.  As you may know, many of the children in these programs have been abused, neglected, and are without any social support or structure in their lives. If anything, these types of programs need more funding.  These facilities are designed to prevent future problems by intervening with current problems.  As you know, mental health care services in North Carolina are currently deplorable, and many people who require such services are ending up in our prisons, emergency rooms, homeless shelters, and morgues, resulting in both increasing long-term human misery and monetary costs.  
These two programs provide services that our state should feel obligated to provide its youth.
Our school system has had a number of students who benefited from treatment from the Wright and Whitaker Schools. I do not believe that if the benefit and worth of these programs was competently evaluated that these proposed cuts would be given a second thought by anyone who cares about the youth of this State.   I understand that the economic situation is dire at this time, and we suggest that rather than taking away from those who already have close to nothing, consider making budget cuts that take a more "top-down" approach.   The closing of these two schools will only succeed in making a bad situation much worse.
I strongly encourage you to withdraw this proposal and to visit these schools and learn more about their mission, structure, and the services they provide to this under-served population of troubled youth in our state.

Respectfully,
