Comment: Dear Governor Perdue, I hope you are NEVER in the position to know what it's like to have a family member suffer with mental illness, but I would like for you to know a little about how this affected my family. My cousin Randy was an smart and loving teenager when he began to show the effects of mental illness. At that time, he was an average, fun-loving kid, with a big mop of curly hair, an impish smile, and a husky laugh that made everyone around him laugh, too. Then his behavior changed. He began to hear voices in his head, began to act inappropriate ways, to do things that didn't make any kind of sense, that were totally unlike him. His diagnosis of Schizophrenia shattered his parents, but they were determined to do all they could for him. In the 70's, there was much less that could be done for those suffering from mental illness, still, his parents tried and tried again to get him the help he needed. He was in and out of a number of facilities for several years, as the rest of us were growing up, learning to drive, having typical teenage fun. I remember our family reunion, at Carolina Beach, in August of 1979. Randy was in a mental hospital at the time. We called him from a pay phone on the board walk and all of the cousins waited for our turn to chat with him, to tell him we loved him, that we wished he was with us. I cannot imagine the torment that Randy went through. He so wanted to be "normal" like the rest of us. He wanted so much to please the parents that he loved, but he knew that he caused them untold tears and worry. His suffering was never ending and inescapable. He could never know if the things he saw were really there and he couldn't get away from the whisperings he heard. On March 3, 1983, he seemed to be in one of his more lucid moods. He and his mother spent an enjoyable evening watching a movie together. When it was over, he kissed his mother good-night, told her he loved her, then went into the basement, where he put a hunting rifle under his chin and pulled the trigger. He was 21 years old. In a week and a half, it will be 26 years since that night, though in many ways, it seems like it happened yesterday. I'm sure it's true for all people who lose loved ones through suicide that you NEVER get over the "Why's" and "What if's". WHAT IF the hunting rifle and the bullets had been disposed of, so Randy hadn't had access? WHAT IF his brother had gotten home just a few minutes earlier, in time to stop him? WHY did this have to happen to our family, to our sweet, talented cousin/nephew/son/brother? WHY would a loving God inflict anyone with such a cruel, tormenting disease? I read the other day that researchers are hoping to isolate a cure for Schizophrenia by 2013. What an answer to prayer that day will be. Still, untold thousands of young people TODAY are suffering like my cousin suffered, from schizophrenia or other mental illnesses. I like to imagine that if my cousin were a young person today, his story would have a different outcome. If he had had the opportunity to attend a facility like the Wright School, he would been around other kids who suffered with similar afflictions, instead of always feeling "different". He would have learned to live with his affliction, without being made to feel that he responsible for it. He would've been been taught how to appreciate and use the many God-given talents which made him unique, instead of being sure that he was "defective", "unworthy" and "a burden". I'd like to imagine that if my cousin had access to a facility like the Wright School, he'd be alive today, with a family of his own. I like to imagine him surviving to face the wrinkles and bulges of middle age alongside me, instead of being eternally 21. I'd like to imagine him as a happy, whole, functioning adult, instead of the anguished and tormented child who pulled that trigger. I did NOT mean to write a letter of this length, which has taken me the better part of a work week to finish, as well as a whole lot of tears. But maybe this letter is my chance to glean something worthwhile out of Randy's fate. If I can influence your decision, to persuade you of the worth of the Wright School and other facilities that treat young people with mental illnesses and persuade you to leave these facilities open, then you will truly be honoring him and his memory. There is a quote that has come to my mind over and over, these last few days, as I've been writing this letter, one that has been attributed to many world leaders throughout the centuries. Gandhi said, "A nation's greatness is measured by how it treats its weakest members." But I like Hubert Humphrey's take on this philosophy the best. He said, "...the moral test of government is how that government treats those who are in the dawn of life, the children; those who are in the twilight of life, the elderly; those who are in the shadows of life; the sick, the needy and the handicapped. " On your Inauguration Day, I watched you take your oath with my daughters, shed a tear and told them that the inauguration of our first female Governor and our first Black President meant that politics - and our country - were forever changed for the better. Please, Governor Perdue, DO THE RIGHT THING by leaving the Wright School - and other mental health facilities - open! Do this for my cousin, Randy, and all the children who still suffer like he did, for those who are still "in the dawn of their lives". Thank you so very much. Sincerely, Teri Johnson Pasley

