RE: Proposal to close Wright and Whitaker Schools



Dear Governor Perdue,



The Chatham County Board of Commissioners is requesting that you reconsider your decision to close both the Wright and Whitaker Schools, which provide critical residential mental health services for children from our county and across the state.  We understand your need to reduce State expenditures in these economically difficult times; however, eliminating these vital programs will not only put the lives of emotionally disturbed children/adolescents who are at risk of needing higher levels of care, but will actually cost the state and local governments considerably more in public expenditures over time.  Moreover, there are currently are no suitable replacements for these residential programs. Thus, even in the short term, the expenditures you might save in these two programs will result in additional and far more costly expenditures when this type of treatment falls completely on the other resources of the State and/or counties. (See the attached background information sheet.) The programs at Wright and Whitaker provide essential treatment for children/adolescents in need by working directly with the parents on how to more effectively communicate with and otherwise manage their young people at home. 



By all accounts these institutions are both programmatically and fiscally efficient and effective. Additionally, these two schools have received overwhelming praise from the population they serve and from the social service and educational professionals in their home communities.  Many of these children and adolescents have been able to return to their families and local schools after treatment.  Professionals with our Orange Person Chatham Area Mental Health Program, which during the last four years has successfully placed fourteen (14) and seven (7) Chatham County children in the Wright and Whitaker schools respectively, have confirmed this.



If these schools are closed, costs for treatment will rise and fall on other resources of the State or those served will be left to their own devices to compensate. The Wright School for instance, costs about $28,000 for the child’s stay. If a group home and day treatment program were the option, that figure goes to something like $64,000.  More importantly, the costs to the children and adolescents, their families and their communities of eliminating these crucial residential services  is incalculable, as our District Court judges will attest.



Most important, these schools actually work. The return to a more normal life and reintegration into the regular school system is far better than hospitalization or inadequate treatment in some other setting.  The low staff turnover rate for both schools attests to the dedication, effectiveness and training of these professionals.



We urge you to keep these schools open and viable. There may be some areas of mental health that are redundant, where costs might be cut, but the Wright and Whitaker Schools are not in that category.



Thank you for considering our urgent request that you reconsider your plans to close these two schools.



Sincerely,



Chairman Dr. George Lucier

For the Board of Chatham County Commissioners





